predict.regsubsets = function(object, newdata, id)
{
    form  = as.formula(object$call[[2]])
    mat   = model.matrix(form, newdata)
    coefi = coef(object, id = id)
    xvars = names(coefi)
    mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

# calculating training and testing errors of all best p models selected via forward selection

for (i in 1:85) {
    
    y_pred_train = predict(regfit_forward, newdata = train_set, id = i)
    y_pred_test  = predict(regfit_forward, newdata = test_set, id = i)
    
    y_pred_train = ifelse(y_pred_train > 0.5, 1, 0)
    y_pred_test  = ifelse(y_pred_test > 0.5, 1, 0)
    
    fwd_train_errors[i] = mean(y_pred_train != train_set[, 86])
    fwd_test_errors[i]  = mean(y_pred_test  != test_set[, 86])
}

With knn regression, the error rate of linear regression varies greatly. The knn performs much better than linear regression. This shows that, when compared to linear regression, knn regression is a very good and superior method for classification. The presence of a single direct strike lowers the training error results. As the number of neighbors increases, the quantity of mistake increases.
